FILE SYSTEM

Linux is a tree like structure everything branches from the root directory which is denoted as a single  forward slash (/) 
to go to the root directory the command would be [ cd / ] and to go back in directory the command would be [ cd .. ]
bin folder - is where all the essential command are stored. 
home folder - stores users and there directory for example if you wanted to access a user you would put [ cd /home/mohamed ].
lib folder - also short for libary is a shared libary where it stores the simular functionalities, such as outputing (instead of the logic of outputing being in each command it will be in the lib folder to save disk space and for functionality reasons)
etc folder - contains system wide configs.
opt folder - anything that doesnt follow linux file system structure is stored in the opt file ( such as google chrome which runs on unix)
proc folder - kernal level info/ procceses that are running opn the computer.
root folder - stores users and there dircetories for the root account( essentilally the same as the home folder but with the rooot account)
boot folder - (the boot process is when you turn on your device computer/ laptop the time from when you press on till the logging in screen displays there are processes running called the boot process) this folder is uesed to boot the device up.
usr folder- conatins the lib/bin and a few more 
media/mnt folder - contains any third party device that you connect to such as a usb stick.



