FILE PERMISSION
    To read file permision we use the command [ ls -l ] which would display something like this  (lrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 1 Mar  4 09:06 filesystem ->) there will be 10 characters, the first character will always refer to the file type 'l' in this case is a linked file also known as a soft link. It can sometimes start with 'd' which stands for directory and when its a normal file it will start with '-'. 
    
    The following 9 chracters (rwx,rwx,rwx) can be split up to 3 groups of 3, they each contain 3 character each "rwx" these stand for "read, write and execute". The first three is for the user , the middle three is for group and the final 3 is for others.
    
    The user is the person who created the file/folder to find this out we can use the following command [ whoami ] which in this case is the root user, you can also find this out by uing the [ls -l] command, which should display something like this (1 root root 1 ) after the string representation this indicates that we are in the root user.
    
    The middle 3 is the group, A group is just a collection of users. when a file is assigned to a group all users in that group get the same permissions for that file, this can be useful for collaborations within projects.

    the final three is the others is everyone else in the machine you can give the permissions to just read the file 


