PROCESSES COMMANDS AND STATES
    - In linux nearly everything running is a process from the terminal itself to the commands inputted are running processes

    
    [ps] - this command is used to show us the processes accociated to the current terminal session 
    [ps a] - shows all processes in different terminal sessions aswell as the unique processesing ID.
    
    [ps au] - shows the associated user that started the process plus all processes in different terminal sessions aswell as the unique processesing ID. aswell as command that started it.
   
    [echo $$] - outputs the the process ID of this current terminal session.
    
    [ps -aux] is used to display all the proceses that are not terminal accociated so everything on the system.

    [ps -f] is used to display detailed full format about running processes showing you UID (user who owns the process) , PID (process ID) PPID(parent process ID which is the process that created the new process), CMD (command that started the process), STIME (start time), TTY (terminal associated with the process).

    [ps -p 1] - is the father of all process every process stems from this process uslly called system d
    [pstree] - displays a visual representation of a process tree stemming from systemd
    
    [top/htop/btop] - give you real time continueous system monitoring which displays running processes, CPU usage, memory(RAM)usage and system load.

    [ps aux --sort=-%mem | head] - this command shows highest ram usage at the top and includes their PID.


    processes have different states you have running states[R] which means the process is currently excuting on CPU, sleeping state[S] which means the process is waiting for something such as input,file or an event(this is an interuptable sleep), uninteruptable sleep[D] state is when the process is waitng for I/OThe process is essentially “paused” until the kernel gets a response., stopped[T] state is when process has been manually paused and Zombie [Z] state is when the process is finished execution but the parent process(processes that it came from) hasnt collected its exit status yet.( normal process flow [1] child process runs [2] child process finshes [3] parent process collects exit status [4] process is fully removed). 

    [Ctrl+c] - is used to terminate processes.
    [Ctrl+z] - is used to stop/pause processes can sometimes be ignored
    [kill -STOP PID] - pause processes using PID cannot be ignore 
    [kill -CONT PID] - resumes processes using PID
    [fg 1] - continues paused processes in the foreground 
    [bg 1] - continue in the background
    [KILL -l] - shows you all the different process signals 
    [pkill] can use it to kill a file using name /PID.

    [lsof] - lists open files and can be used to check specfic process and port.

